<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXXON AGREES TO PROBE OF DESTROYED RECORDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANCHORAGE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bowing to state demands, Exxon agreed Thursday to submit to a state of Alaska 
inquiry over the destruction of computer records in the nation's worst oil 
spill. 
</P>
<P>
"They have indicated they were willing to cooperate in such an investigation," 
said Alaska Atty. Gen. Doug Baily. 
</P>
<P>
Exxon, in statements from Houston, declared that no spill documents were 
destroyed, only computer copies. The same statement made no mention of Alaska 
demands that Exxon submit to an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
But Baily announced Thursday afternoon that lawyers for both sides were meeting 
in Anchorage to work out an agreement that would allow the state to get sworn 
testimony from Exxon officials within two weeks. 
</P>
