<P>
14,000 CIGARETTES GO UP IN SMOKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WARR ACRES, Okla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 14,000 cigarettes went up in huge puffs of smoke outside a suburban 
Oklahoma City drugstore, and the owner said he will never sell tobacco again. 
</P>
<P>
Pharmacist Kenneth Henderson dumped about 700 packs of cigarettes, worth about 
$1,000, into a trash can Wednesday and tossed in a lighted match to burn them. 
</P>
<P>
Henderson said he decided to quit selling cigarettes as his part of a 
"NonDependence Day" observance by the American Lung Assn. 
</P>
<P>
"It just doesn't make sense for us to sell prescription items in the back to 
make people well, and sell cigarettes at another location to make them sick," 
Henderson said. 
</P>
