<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; 
</P>
<P>
KOLL PLANS $50-MILLION OFFICE TOWER WITH JAPANESE PARTNERS NEAR AIRPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Michael Flagg, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Koll Co., the big Newport Beach developer, said it would build a $50-million, 
11-story office tower in partnership with a Japanese company at Koll Center 
Irvine near John Wayne Airport. 
</P>
<P>
Koll said it would start construction in August near Von Karman Avenue and 
Michelson Drive. The building will be a duplicate of the Transamerica Building, 
a white, precast concrete office tower built four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Koll's partner in the building is Zenitaka Corp., which acquired the 
joint-venture rights from Transamerica Occidental Life Insurance Cos. 
</P>
<P>
Zenitaka, a 100-year-old contractor, acquired in the same deal the 
joint-venture rights with Koll to a second site nearby, Koll said. Both sites 
are next to the Transamerica building and the five-story Marine National Bank 
building, which are joint ventures of Koll and the life insurance company. 
</P>
<P>
Gensler &amp; Associates designed the new, 234,500-square-foot building, which 
is scheduled for completion in 1990, Koll said. 
</P>
<P>
Koll Center Irvine is a 104-acre, $1-billion office and retailing center on 
both sides of the San Diego Freeway at Von Karman Avenue. The new building will 
be the 13th in the center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Drawing of 11-story tower Koll plans near Wayne airport. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
