<P>
FORD TO BUILD PLANT IN PORTUGAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DEARBORN, Mich. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. will build a $120-million plant in Portugal to make automobile 
radios, compact disc players and other audio components, the company said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
An agreement to build the 230,000-square-foot plant was signed by Oscar B. Marx 
III, executive director of Ford's Automotive Components Group, and Joaquim 
Ferreira do Amaral, Portugal's minister of commerce and tourism. 
</P>
<P>
The plant, about 40 miles from Lisbon on the Setubal peninsula, will begin 
operations in 1992 and employ about 1,700 people. Its products will be used 
mostly in Ford assembly plants in Europe, said spokeswoman Maureen Mazzatenta. 
</P>
